There’s no mutating happening here, for example:  if cond:
      X = “yes”
  else:
      X = “no”

X is only ever assigned once, it’s actually still purely functional. And in Rust or Lisp or other expression languages, you can do stuff like this:  let X = if cond { “yes” } else { “no” };

That’s a lot nicer than a trinary operator!

You could do an absolutely disgusting IIFE if you need the curly brace spice in your life, instead of a typical JS ternary.  const y = (() => {
    if (x) {
      return true;
    } else {
      return false;
  })();

